english:
  title: On the Character of Nature
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Nature is the Heavenly Principle dwelling within the human heart. Humanity, righteousness, propriety, and wisdom are its names. In Heaven it is called Principle; in humans it is called Nature. Yet their substance is one. That which rests still and unmoved is its essence; that which responds and flows forth is its function. Compassion, shame, deference, and the discernment of right and wrong are the function revealed outwardly. By observing what manifests without, we can know what rests within. This is what we call Original Nature.

    Yet because our inborn endowments are unequal, there arise differences in darkness and light, strength and weakness. This is what we call Nature of Material Force. Mencius spoke of the goodness of nature—a teaching that traces things to their root and source, yet does not address the Nature of Material Force. Xunzi spoke of nature's evil; Yangzi of mixed good and evil; Hanzi of three grades of nature. All these speak only of the Nature of Material Force, neglecting Original Nature.

    Original Nature is the same in Yao and Shun as in the common person. Yet the Nature of Material Force differs infinitely. But through earnest study and effort, we can transform our material endowment, and then Original Nature manifests right here. Consider a lustrous pearl: in clear water it gleams; in murky water it dims. Yet when we cleanse the murky water until it runs clear, it becomes no different from a pearl always in clear water. Its radiance is not sought from without; its dimness is not its true nature. It depends only on our power to cleanse.

    To follow the natural course of this Nature is the Way. To walk this Way and embody it in the heart is Virtue. Whoever becomes clear in understanding the meaning of this character can know Nature; can know the Way and Virtue as well. When knowing is luminous, action becomes correct. Yet it has never been so that one can act rightly while remaining in darkness.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Ha Ryun (河崙, 1347-1416) was a Korean Neo-Confucian scholar during the early Joseon Dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: This essay synthesizes the Neo-Confucian philosophy of human nature, particularly drawing on Zhu Xi's distinction between Original Nature (本然之性) and the Nature of Material Force (氣質之性).
  - key: ''
    value: The pearl metaphor illustrates how the inherent goodness of human nature remains constant, while its manifestation depends on the refinement of one's material endowment through learning and self-cultivation.
